'''Thomas Worrall (Tom) Kent''' [[Order of Canada|CC]] (born [[April 3]], [[1922]]) is a [[Canada|Canadian]] economist, journalist, editor, public servant and industrialist.

Born in [[Stafford]], [[England]], Kent graduated from [[Oxford University]] and worked as a journalist for [[The Guardian|The Manchester Guardian]] and [[The Economist]].  In 1954 he immigrated to Canada to become editor of the [[Winnipeg Free Press]].  He later served as deputy minister of immigration in the government of [[Lester Pearson]]. <ref>{{cite news
|url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20080424.wcoessay0426/BNStory/Front/home
|title=Canada is much more than a hotel
|accessdate=2008-06-01
|date=April 25, 2008
|publisher=The Globe and Mail
|first=Tom|last=Kent}}</ref> In 1980 he was appointed to chair the [[Royal Commission on Newspapers]], which would become known as the ''Kent Commission''.

In [[1979]], he was made an Officer of the [[Order of Canada]] and was promoted to Companion in [[2001]].

